Title: Brownsville Girl
Comment: A high-attention sprawling epic of lost love, and “the only real excuse” for Dylan’s least-loved album, this song is an obsessive, meandering 11 minute piece of poetry co-written by Bob and a playwright. I don’t expect anyone to love this like I do, or probably even like it, but it’s my life’s mission to spread the gospel of its perfection in the hopes that it reaches just one other appreciative soul. This song gives you what you give it. I hope it makes you happy!

Title: How You Gonna Keep 'Em Down On the Farm
Comment:
"World War I-era popular song that rose to popularity after the war had ended. The lyrics highlight concern that soldiers would not want to return to their family farms after experiencing the European city life and high culture of Paris during World War I." 
Fun fact -- the line "once a farmer, always a jay" refers to a "jay" as a country person, and is the origin of the term "jaywalking" -- when country folks came to cities and didn't know street crossing etiquette.
